{"title_page": "Ruth Roland", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Ruth Roland\n|image        = Ruthroland.jpg\n|imageupright = \n|caption      = \n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1892|8|26}}\n|birth_place  = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1937|9|22|1892|8|26}}\n|death_place  = [[Hollywood]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n|occupation   = Actress, producer\n|years_active = 1911\u20131936\n|spouse       = Lionel T. Kent <small>(m. 1917\u2013div.1919)</small><br>[[Ben Bard]] <small>(m. 1929)</small>\n|mother       =\n|father       = \n|relatives     =\n}}\n'''Ruth Roland''' (August 26, 1892 \u2013 September 22, 1937) was an American stage and film actress and film producer.<ref name=\"record-argus1937\">{{cite news |author=Staff writer |editor-last=Morrison |editor-first=John L. |date=September 28, 1937 |title=Ruth Roland, Serial Star, Left Real Estate Fortune |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/12986330/|newspaper=The Record-Argus |volume=89 |issue=227 |page=3 |publisher=Advance Argus Company |location=[[Greenville, Pennsylvania]] |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref>https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QGRR-2JBK</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nRuth Roland was born in [[San Francisco]], California to Elizabeth Lillian Hauser and Jack Roland. Her father managed a [[Theater (building)|theatre]], and she became a [[Child actor|child actress]] who went on to work in [[vaudeville]]. At age 12, she was the youngest student at [[Hollywood High School]], having attended the school around 1904 or 1905 (there is debate on this date). Roland was Hollywood High School's first homegrown [[movie star]].<ref>[http://www.silent-movies.com/Taylorology/Taylor36.txt silent-movies.com Ruth Roland profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020041630/http://silent-movies.com/Taylorology/Taylor36.txt |date=October 20, 2006 }}, silent-movies.com; accessed May 6, 2014.</ref>\n\nShe was hired by director [[Sidney Olcott]] who had seen her on stage in [[New York City]]. She appeared in her first film, ''A Chance Shot'', for [[Kalem Company|Kalem Studios]] in 1911, becoming the [[Leading actor|leading actress]] of their new West Coast studio.<ref>{{cite book |author=Staff writer |year=1924 |title=Stars of the Photoplay |url=https://archive.org/stream/starsofphotoplay00phot#page/n217/ |publisher=Photoplay Magazine |location=Chicago, Illinois |page=206 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>  After  [[Gene Gauntier]]'s departure from Kalem, she became billed as the new \"Kalem Girl.\" She eventually became [[Supervisor|overseer]] of \"Kalem House\" where all the actors lived.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nRoland left Kalem and went on to even more fame at [[Balboa Amusement Producing Company|Balboa Films]], where she was under contract from 1914 to 1917. In 1915 she appeared in a 14-episode [[adventure film]] [[Serial film|serial]] titled ''[[The Red Circle (serial)|The Red Circle]]''. A shrewd businessperson, she established her own [[production company]], Ruth Roland Serials, and signed a [[Film distribution|distribution]] deal with [[Path\u00e9]] to make seven new multi-episode serials that proved very successful.\n\nBetween 1909 and 1927, Roland appeared in more than 200 films. She appeared in an early [[Color motion picture film|color feature film]] ''[[Cupid Angling]]'' (1918) made in the Natural Color process invented by [[Leon Douglass|Leon F. Douglass]], and filmed in the [[Lake Lagunitas]] area of [[Marin County, California]].\n\nRoland worked the film business until 1930 when she made her first [[talkie]]. Although her voice worked well enough on screen, now entering her forties she returned to performing in [[Theatre|live theatre]], making only one more film appearance in 1936.\n\n==Personal life==\nRoland was married to Lionel T. Kent on May 16, 1917.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |title=Ruth Roland |date=June 7, 1917 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/119634732 |location=[[Detroit]], Michigan |newspaper=Detroit Free Press |volume=82 |issue=253 |page=8 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The marriage was short-lived:  they separated on September 2, 1918, and divorced on April 2, 1919.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |title=Ruth Roland is Divorced from Lieut. Kent |date=April 2, 1919 |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=LAH19190402.1.3 |location=Los Angeles, California |newspaper=Los Angeles Evening Herald |volume=44 |issue=130 |edition=Night |pages=1, 7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |title=Picture Patter |date=April 19, 1919 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/174686628/ |location=Seattle, Washington |newspaper=The Seattle Star |volume=22 |issue=51 |page=3 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> On February 14, 1929 she married fellow actor [[Ben Bard]], who also had a stage acting background, and ran a [[Hollywood]] [[Drama school|acting school]] after they married.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |title=Ruth Roland and New Hubby-to-Be |date=11 February 1929 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/154137409/ |location=Wilmington, Delaware |newspaper=The News Journal |volume=62 |issue=36 |page=20 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> They were together until the end of Roland's life.\n\n==Death==\nRuth Roland died of [[cancer]] in 1937, aged 45, in Hollywood and is interred near her husband in the [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Glendale, California]].<ref name=\"Ellenberger2001\">{{cite book|last=Ellenberger|first=Allan R.|title=Celebrities in Los Angeles Cemeteries: A Directory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8bOJCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA68|date=1 May 2001|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-0983-9|pages=68}}</ref>\n\nFor her contribution to the motion picture industry, Ruth Roland received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 6220 [[Hollywood Boulevard]] on February 8, 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/ruth-roland |title=Ruth Roland |website=Hollywood Walk of Fame |publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce |access-date=4 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/ruth-roland/|title=Ruth Roland|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref> In 1979, a concrete box containing Roland's personal film collection was discovered buried in the backyard of Roland's house, and donated to the UCLA Film Archives by her heirs in 1980.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff writer |title=UCLA Acquires Roland Films |date=14 March 1980 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107594297/ |newspaper=The Indianapolis Star |volume=77 |issue=283 |page=32 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nA Matrimonial Martyr.jpg|''A Matrimonial Martyr'' (1916)\nThe Sultana.jpg|''The Sultana'' (1916)\nThe Neglected Wife.jpg|''The Neglected Wife'' (1917)\nHands Up 1918.jpg|''Hands Up'' (1918)\nRuth Roland 1919.jpg|''The Tiger's Trail'' (1919)\nRuthRolandTimberQueen1922.jpg|''[[The Timber Queen]]'' (1922)\n</gallery>\n[[File:Ruth Roland 1916 2.jpg|thumb|Roland in 1916]]\n[[File:Ruth Roland on the cover of Motion Picture Classic, January 1922, cover by Benjamin Eggleston..jpg|thumb|Ruth Roland on the cover of [[Motion Picture Classic]], January 1922, cover by Benjamin Eggleston (1867-1937).<ref name=platnick>{{cite book |last=Platnick |first= Norman I.|author-link= |date= February 2017|title= Lady of Mystery: A Collector's Guide to Edward Eggleston version 3.5|url= https://enchantmentink.com/edward.php|location= |publisher= |page= 5 |isbn= |quote= those Motion Picture Classic covers, published from at least July, 1921 through August, 1922, were actually done by Benjamin Eggleston...([https://enchantmentink.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/books/Enchantment+Ink+-+Eggleston.pdf PDF version book released by Platnick's son]).}}</ref>]]\n* ''A Chance Shot'' (1911)\n* ''He Who Laughs Last'' (1911)\n* ''Ruth Roland, the Kalem Girl'' (1912)\n* ''Pulque Pete and the Opera Troupe'' (1912)\n* ''The Raiders from Double L Ranch'' (1913)\n* ''Gertie Gets the Cash'' (1914)\n* ''[[The Deadly Battle at Hicksville]]'' (1914)\n* ''The Pursuit of Pleasure'' (1915)\n* ''Who Pays?'' (1915)\n* ''[[The Red Circle (serial)|The Red Circle]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[Comrade John]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[A Matrimonial Martyr]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[The Sultana]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[The Devil's Bait]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[The Neglected Wife]]'' (1917)\n* ''The Fringe of Society'' (1917)\n* ''[[Hands Up (serial)|Hands Up]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[Cupid Angling]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[The Tiger's Trail]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[The Adventures of Ruth]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[Ruth of the Rockies]]'' (1920)\n* ''[[The Avenging Arrow]]'' (1921)\n* ''[[White Eagle (1922 serial)|White Eagle]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[The Timber Queen]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[Haunted Valley]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[Ruth of the Range]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[Dollar Down]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[Where the Worst Begins]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[The Masked Woman]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Reno (1930 film)|Reno]]'' (1930)\n* ''From Nine to Nine'' (1936)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Balboa Films \u2013 A History and Filmography of the Silent Film Studio'' {{ISBN|0-7864-0496-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|0738082}}\n* {{Find a Grave|5157}}\n* [http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/person/6942/ruth-roland Literature on Ruth Roland]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roland, Ruth}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Film serial actresses]]\n[[Category:Burials at Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)]]\n[[Category:Actresses from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:American stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Actresses from the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:American women film producers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Ruth Roland\n|image        = Ruthroland.jpg\n|imageupright = \n|caption      = \n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1892|8|26}}\n|birth_place  = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1937|9|22|1892|8|26}}\n|death_place  = [[Hollywood]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n|occupation   = Actress, producer\n|years_active = 1911\u20131936\n|spouse       = Lionel T. Kent <small>(m. 1917\u2013div.1919)</small><br>[[Ben Bard]] <small>(m. 1929)</small>\n|mother       =\n|father       = \n|relatives     =\n}}\n'''Ruth Roland''' (August 26, 1892 \u2013 September 22, 1937) was an American stage and film actress and film producer.<ref name=\"record-argus1937\">{{cite news |author=Staff writer |editor-last=Morrison |editor-first=John L. |date=September 28, 1937 |title=Ruth Roland, Serial Star, Left Real Estate Fortune |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/12986330/|newspaper=The Record-Argus |volume=89 |issue=227 |page=3 |publisher=Advance Argus Company |location=[[Greenville, Pennsylvania]] |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref>https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QGRR-2JBK</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nRuth Roland was born in [[San Francisco]], California to Elizabeth Lillian Hauser and Jack Roland. Her father managed a [[Theater (building)|theatre]], and she became a [[Child actor|child actress]] who went on to work in [[vaudeville]]. At age 12, she was the youngest student at [[Hollywood High School]], having attended the school around 1904 or 1905 (there is debate on this date). Roland was Hollywood High School's first homegrown [[movie star]].<ref>[http://www.silent-movies.com/Taylorology/Taylor36.txt silent-movies.com Ruth Roland profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020041630/http://silent-movies.com/Taylorology/Taylor36.txt |date=October 20, 2006 }}, silent-movies.com; accessed May 6, 2014.</ref>\n\nShe was hired by director [[Sidney Olcott]] who had seen her on stage in [[New York City]]. She appeared in her first film, ''A Chance Shot'', for [[Kalem Company|Kalem Studios]] in 1911, becoming the [[Leading actor|leading actress]] of their new West Coast studio.<ref>{{cite book |author=Staff writer |year=1924 |title=Stars of the Photoplay |url=https://archive.org/stream/starsofphotoplay00phot#page/n217/ |publisher=Photoplay Magazine |location=Chicago, Illinois |page=206 |via=[[Internet Archive]]}}</ref>  After  [[Gene Gauntier]]'s departure from Kalem, she became billed as the new \"Kalem Girl.\" She eventually became [[Supervisor|overseer]] of \"Kalem House\" where all the actors lived.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nRoland left Kalem and went on to even more fame at [[Balboa Amusement Producing Company|Balboa Films]], where she was under contract from 1914 to 1917. In 1915 she appeared in a 14-episode [[adventure film]] [[Serial film|serial]] titled ''[[The Red Circle (serial)|The Red Circle]]''. A shrewd businessperson, she established her own [[production company]], Ruth Roland Serials, and signed a [[Film distribution|distribution]] deal with [[Path\u00e9]] to make seven new multi-episode serials that proved very successful.\n\nBetween 1909 and 1927, Roland appeared in more than 200 films. She appeared in an early [[Color motion picture film|color feature film]] ''[[Cupid Angling]]'' (1918) made in the Natural Color process invented by [[Leon Douglass|Leon F. Douglass]], and filmed in the [[Lake Lagunitas]] area of [[Marin County, California]].\n\nRoland worked the film business until 1930 when she made her first [[talkie]]. Although her voice worked well enough on screen, now entering her forties she returned to performing in [[Theatre|live theatre]], making only one more film appearance in 1936.\n\n==Personal life==\nRoland was married to Lionel T. Kent on May 16, 1917.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |title=Ruth Roland |date=June 7, 1917 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/119634732 |location=[[Detroit]], Michigan |newspaper=Detroit Free Press |volume=82 |issue=253 |page=8 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The marriage was short-lived:  they separated on September 2, 1918, and divorced on April 2, 1919.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |title=Ruth Roland is Divorced from Lieut. Kent |date=April 2, 1919 |url=https://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=LAH19190402.1.3 |location=Los Angeles, California |newspaper=Los Angeles Evening Herald |volume=44 |issue=130 |edition=Night |pages=1, 7}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |title=Picture Patter |date=April 19, 1919 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/174686628/ |location=Seattle, Washington |newspaper=The Seattle Star |volume=22 |issue=51 |page=3 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> On February 14, 1929 she married fellow actor [[Ben Bard]], who also had a stage acting background, and ran a [[Hollywood]] [[Drama school|acting school]] after they married.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |title=Ruth Roland and New Hubby-to-Be |date=11 February 1929 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/154137409/ |location=Wilmington, Delaware |newspaper=The News Journal |volume=62 |issue=36 |page=20 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> They were together until the end of Roland's life.\n\n==Death==\nRuth Roland died of [[cancer]] in 1937, aged 45, in Hollywood and is interred near her husband in the [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park Cemetery]] in [[Glendale, California]].<ref name=\"Ellenberger2001\">{{cite book|last=Ellenberger|first=Allan R.|title=Celebrities in Los Angeles Cemeteries: A Directory|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8bOJCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA68|date=1 May 2001|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-0983-9|pages=68}}</ref>\n\nFor her contribution to the motion picture industry, Ruth Roland received a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] at 6220 [[Hollywood Boulevard]] on February 8, 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/ruth-roland |title=Ruth Roland |website=Hollywood Walk of Fame |publisher=Hollywood Chamber of Commerce |access-date=4 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://projects.latimes.com/hollywood/star-walk/ruth-roland/|title=Ruth Roland|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref> In 1979, a concrete box containing Roland's personal film collection was discovered buried in the backyard of Roland's house, and donated to the UCLA Film Archives by her heirs in 1980.<ref>{{cite news |author=Staff writer |title=UCLA Acquires Roland Films |date=14 March 1980 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/107594297/ |newspaper=The Indianapolis Star |volume=77 |issue=283 |page=32 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n<gallery mode=packed>\nA Matrimonial Martyr.jpg|''A Matrimonial Martyr'' (1916)\nThe Sultana.jpg|''The Sultana'' (1916)\nThe Neglected Wife.jpg|''The Neglected Wife'' (1917)\nHands Up 1918.jpg|''Hands Up'' (1918)\nRuth Roland 1919.jpg|''The Tiger's Trail'' (1919)\nRuthRolandTimberQueen1922.jpg|''[[The Timber Queen]]'' (1922)\n</gallery>\n[[File:Ruth Roland 1916 2.jpg|thumb|Roland in 1916]]\n[[File:Ruth Roland on the cover of Motion Picture Classic, January 1922, cover by Edward Mason Eggleston.jpg|thumb|Ruth Roland on the cover of [[Motion Picture Classic]], January 1922, cover by Benjamin Eggleston (1867-1937).<ref name=platnick>{{cite book |last=Platnick |first= Norman I.|author-link= |date= February 2017|title= Lady of Mystery: A Collector's Guide to Edward Eggleston version 3.5|url= https://enchantmentink.com/edward.php|location= |publisher= |page= 5 |isbn= |quote= those Motion Picture Classic covers, published from at least July, 1921 through August, 1922, were actually done by Benjamin Eggleston...([https://enchantmentink.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/books/Enchantment+Ink+-+Eggleston.pdf PDF version book released by Platnick's son]).}}</ref>]]\n* ''A Chance Shot'' (1911)\n* ''He Who Laughs Last'' (1911)\n* ''Ruth Roland, the Kalem Girl'' (1912)\n* ''Pulque Pete and the Opera Troupe'' (1912)\n* ''The Raiders from Double L Ranch'' (1913)\n* ''Gertie Gets the Cash'' (1914)\n* ''[[The Deadly Battle at Hicksville]]'' (1914)\n* ''The Pursuit of Pleasure'' (1915)\n* ''Who Pays?'' (1915)\n* ''[[The Red Circle (serial)|The Red Circle]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[Comrade John]]'' (1915)\n* ''[[A Matrimonial Martyr]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[The Sultana]]'' (1916)\n* ''[[The Devil's Bait]]'' (1917)\n* ''[[The Neglected Wife]]'' (1917)\n* ''The Fringe of Society'' (1917)\n* ''[[Hands Up (serial)|Hands Up]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[Cupid Angling]]'' (1918)\n* ''[[The Tiger's Trail]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[The Adventures of Ruth]]'' (1919)\n* ''[[Ruth of the Rockies]]'' (1920)\n* ''[[The Avenging Arrow]]'' (1921)\n* ''[[White Eagle (1922 serial)|White Eagle]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[The Timber Queen]]'' (1922)\n* ''[[Haunted Valley]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[Ruth of the Range]]'' (1923)\n* ''[[Dollar Down]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[Where the Worst Begins]]'' (1925)\n* ''[[The Masked Woman]]'' (1927)\n* ''[[Reno (1930 film)|Reno]]'' (1930)\n* ''From Nine to Nine'' (1936)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Balboa Films \u2013 A History and Filmography of the Silent Film Studio'' {{ISBN|0-7864-0496-5}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|0738082}}\n* {{Find a Grave|5157}}\n* [http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/person/6942/ruth-roland Literature on Ruth Roland]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roland, Ruth}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n[[Category:American silent film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[